The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to plunder and war, and in which the growing production capacity of recent decades causes more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, "The Limits to Growth," has influenced the environmental movement up to today.
The optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, the standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
From their opponents, they are seen as "economists of abundance," who trust the market, which is allegedly able to solve all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see whether the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this I have tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a rating list of the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender relations, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists answered the same question: What were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including projections up to 2050.
Using classical economic evaluations of all factors from casualties, health damages, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands up to higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the scale of the problem, it is compared to the total available resources for its solution.
By this means, the size of the problem becomes clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let us consider the gender inequality.
In essence, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the global workforce was female.
What are the losses resulting from this small proportion?
Even when we take into account the higher costs of educating women and the fact that someone must perform unpaid housework, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor force participation rate and smaller income gaps, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is likely to be very surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring about an overall growing net benefit – which could rise to as much as 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefit outweighs the cost.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
Even though it reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems such as wetlands, corresponding to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, which dramatically reduces the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs, which justify cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the rating list also shows us that the largest environmental problem worldwide is indoor air pollution, putting things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating, which corresponds to a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in the year 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
Most health indicators have improved worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy remained largely unchanged.
The magnitude of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and is likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The greatest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
In 1970, for example, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than $2.5 billion on vaccines and have pledged an additional $10 billion.
Through the efforts of the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, the number of polio cases has been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to an astonishing 32% of global GDP.
Today they have fallen to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Although optimists are not entirely correct in all aspects (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century likely costs about 1% of global GDP annually, and in some places significantly more), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the overall trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available for their eradication, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no problems left.
Although they have become smaller in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still significant.
But realists should gradually get used to the idea that the world has greatly improved.
In addition, the rating list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not align our view of the future with the worst stories or the loudest interest groups, but with objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
